Threat:
The remote SSL/TLS server is vulnerable to FREAK attack when:
1.The "RSA+EXPORT" ciphers are supported; 
2.The size of the RSA public key in certificate is not stronger than 1024; 
3.The temporary RSA key size is less than 1024; 
4.The temporary RSA key is stable(used multiple times);  

Only SSLv3 and TLSv1 are potentially vulnerable

Solution_y:
No solution available from Linux vendors yet.Workaround:As per upstream, because of the way scp is based on a historical protocol called rcp which relies on that style of argument passing and therefore encounters expansion problems. Making changes to how the scp command line works breaks the pattern used by scp consumers. Upstream therefore recommends the use of rsync in the place of scp for better security. More details about supported alternatives available at Red Hat guide.
(https://access.redhat.com/articles/5284081
)

